---
const title = "WordPress";
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title={title}>
  <h2>What is WordPress?</h2>
  <p>
    WordPress is the most popular Content Management System (CMS) currently
    running on the web, with about
    <a
      href="https://w3techs.com/technologies/history_overview/content_management"
      >59 percent market share</a
    >. WordPress achieved this because, unlike competitors like Wix and
    SquareSpace, the codebase is open source, meaning anyone can <a
      href="https://github.com/WordPress/WordPress">download it</a
    > and choose to host it wherever they want. The company behind WordPress is <a
      href="https://automattic.com/">Automattic</a
    >, and they run:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href="https://wordpress.com/">WordPress.com</a> (the commercial arm which
      offers hosting and support) and
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://wordpress.org">WordPress.org</a> (which hosts documentation,
      community resources, and the open source software).
    </li>
  </ul>
  <hr />
  <h2>Running WordPress</h2>
  <p>
    You can test WordPress without any installation or hosting by going to <a
      href="https://my.wordpress.net/"
      target="_blank">my.wordpress.net</a
    >.
  </p>
  <p>
    To run WordPress on your own computer, we will use
    <a href="https://developer.wordpress.com/studio/">WordPress Studio</a>,
    which is a software that makes it easy to locally host a PHP/MySQL
    environment to run WordPress.
  </p>
  <hr />
  <h2>Themes and Plugins</h2>
  <p>
    Part of the popularity of WordPress comes from the fact that it can extended
    with themes and plugins.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Themes</strong> change the appearance of your WordPress website. Besides
    the themes
    <a href="https://wordpress.org/themes/">themes on WordPress.org</a>, there
    are several other for-pay sites on the web (for instance,
    <a href="https://www.elegantthemes.com/gallery/divi/">Divi</a> is a theme that
    allows you to customize with a visual interface in the admin).
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong><a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins">Plugins</a></strong> extend the
    functionality of your WordPress site.
  </p>
</Layout>
